def returnCityDistanceData(dataframeTemp,columns):    
    valueOfStat=columns
    newTableForDistance=pd.DataFrame(columns=["Value","Count"])   
    firstColumn=pd.Series(valueOfStat)
    newTableForDistance["Value"]=firstColumn
    valCountOfStat=dataframeTemp[dataframeTemp["Venue Category"].isin(valueOfStat)]
    category_count=valCountOfStat["Venue Category"].value_counts().reset_index()
    category_count.columns=["Value","Count"]

    #print(category_count)
    result_city_data=newTableForDistance.set_index('Value').join(category_count.set_index('Value'),rsuffix='_2')
    result_city_data=result_city_data.drop("Count",axis=1)
    result_city_data=result_city_data.reset_index()
    result_city_data.style
    
    return result_city_data

#result=toronto_venues[toronto_venues["Venue Category"]=="Asian Restaurant"]
returnCityDistanceData(newyork_venues,valueOfStat).style

print(returnCityDistanceData(newyork_venues,valueOfStat))
print("---- Toronto venu count ---")
print(returnCityDistanceData(toronto_venues,valueOfStat))
print("---- Berlin venu count ---")
print(returnCityDistanceData(berlin_venues,valueOfStat))

Note that spatial.distance.cosine computes the distance, and not the similarity.¶

we must subtract the value from 1 to get the similarity.¶

from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_distances

newYork=returnCityDistanceData(newyork_venues,valueOfStat)
toronto=returnCityDistanceData(toronto_venues,valueOfStat)
berlin=returnCityDistanceData(berlin_venues,valueOfStat)

valueOfStatForDistance=["City","Café","Italian Restaurant","Coffee Shop",
                         "Bakery","Supermarket",
                        'Sushi Restaurant',
                        "Spa",'Restaurant',"Asian Restaurant",
                        "Burger Joint"]

data=["New York","Toronto","Berlin"]
dfCity=pd.DataFrame(columns=valueOfStatForDistance)
dfCity["City"]=data
dfCity.iloc[0,1:]=newYork["Count_2"].to_list()
dfCity.iloc[1,1:]=toronto["Count_2"].to_list()
dfCity.iloc[2,1:]=berlin["Count_2"].to_list()
#print(dfCity)

#print(dfCity)    
print(dfCity.iloc[0,1:])


df_1_dropped = dfCity.drop(['City'], axis=1)
df_1=dfCity.set_index(['City'])


resultDistance=pd.DataFrame(1-cosine_distances(df_1_dropped.values, df_1_dropped.values), index=df_1.index, columns=df_1.index)
resultDistance=resultDistance.astype(float)
resultDistance=resultDistance.reset_index()
resultDistance.style.background_gradient(cmap='Blues')

def one_hot_encoding(dataframeTemp_venues):
    # one hot encoding
    dframe_onehot = pd.get_dummies(dataframeTemp_venues[['Venue Category']], prefix="", prefix_sep="")

    # add neighborhood column back to dataframe
    dframe_onehot['Neighbourhood'] = dataframeTemp_venues['Neighbourhood']

    # move neighborhood column to the first column
    fixed_columns = [dframe_onehot.columns[-1]] + list(dframe_onehot.columns[:-1])
    dframe_onehot = dframe_onehot[fixed_columns]
    #toronto_to_be_clustred=toronto_onehot[["Neighbourhood","Coffee Shop","Pub","Mediterranean Restaurant","Shopping Mall"]]
    print(dframe_onehot.shape)
    return dframe_onehot

# set color scheme for the clusters
x = np.arange(kclusters)
ys = [i + x + (i*x)**2 for i in range(kclusters)]
colors_array = cm.rainbow(np.linspace(0, 1, len(ys)))
rainbow = [colors.rgb2hex(i) for i in colors_array]

# add markers to the map
#theZeorLabel=toronto_merged1.loc[toronto_merged1['Cluster_Labels'] == 0, toronto_merged1.columns[[1] + list(range(1, toronto_merged1.shape[1]))]]

    label = folium.Popup(str(poi) + ' Cluster ' + str(cluster), parse_html=True)
    folium.CircleMarker(
        [lat, lon],
        radius=5,
        clustered_marker = True,
        popup=label,
        color=rainbow[cluster-1],
        fill=True,

        new_tor_barchart_data.loc["Toronto",column_name]=0
        new_tor_barchart_data.loc["New York",column_name]=datas["New York"]
